results.notes:
Two NJMA foray collections (3 + 1) found by unknown foray participants.
In the thumbnail photo, the fruitbody on the far right is the second collection. The four mushrooms look the same and stain the same (red and blue) in the exposed context, and thus are believed to be the same species. I didn’t separate the first 3 fruitbodies upon cutting and drying (Collection A). The “far right” basidiome is stored separately as Collection B.
The next image shows the same 4 mushrooms plus one more (with a dog-legged stipe with leaf stuck to it) that I added in error, thinking it was more of the same. That mushroom is undoubtedly another species because, unlike the “quartet”, its flesh doesn’t stain at all and the overall morphology looks a bit different when one takes a closer look. I think it could be a very dark example of L. albellum. It will be posted in a separate observation.
Even though the red-and-blue staining of the exposed flesh perhaps suggest a birch-associated scaber stalk in the snellii group, I don’t think it to be the case. The caps are dark grayish-brown and the stipital scabers are very small and densely packed on the ridges of the textured stipe. The scabers accentuate a noticeable reticulated surface pattern that is so uncommon in Leccinum. I haven’t seen such an ornamentation in any of the other other representatives of sect. Scabra, and I believe this collection to be a species I am not familiar with.

results.notes: We all thought this was a Cortinarius. It looked like C caperatus without the veil or white bloom on cap. The cap is Surf yellow (Ridgeway), 5cm with a low bump in th middle, silky with a wavy edge. The stipe is 8cm x 1cm, off white with a few brown bits stuck to the stipe. Under the cap the stipe is light blue. The substrate was white when the fungus was cut, not blue. The base is slightly swollen with a twist. Gills were clay brown, turning brown when sitting. The gills are subdecurrent. The spores are 8 microns. subglobose, not ornamented with an oil drop in some and thick walls. Not typical for Cortinarius. No chemical reactions.

results.notes: A single fruiting body growing under a sole planted Tilia cordata (European basswood) near a residential building. Unfortunately, the stipe base was not excavated intact due to the wet, yet still hard clay soil and the fragile nature of the stipe/velar tissue. In prior years this tree gave rise to A. phalloides, Cortinarius flavescentipes (both posted to MO and the latter sequenced), as well as a brown-capped russula that was not collected or even photographed. Hence, I suspect this grisette could also be a European transplant, although a species native to NA, like the common A. rooseveltensis, might be just conveniently hitching a ride. There is another basswood some 8-10 yards away and are some white pines nearby around a residential building; however, I doubt that the pines can host these mushrooms as their tree roots need to go under the building foundation to reach the fruiting spot. This material was saved and will eventually be sequenced.

The Weirdest Magic Mushroom Strain Might Be the Enigma
By Graham PilgerAugust 28, 2023
Deep within the heart of mycology lies a mysterythe Enigma mushroom. The name alone sparks intrigue. Among the vast array of fungi, this strain certainly stands apart, a luminary in the captivating world of Psilocybe cubensis.

My Experience with These Mutant Mushrooms
Theres a kaleidoscope of natures surprises in the realm of mushroom cultivation. One quickly realizes that the journey is as unpredictable as it is fascinating. In my own forays into growing these enigmatic fungi, Ive encountered a wide spectrum of mushroom idiosyncrasies.

RELATED: The 6 Best Mushroom Growing Kits According to Our Expert

Each batch of mushrooms tells its own tale, filled with drama, quirks, and unexpected turns. There have been instances where one mushroom boldly grows atop another, establishing its dominance in a surreal display of nature. Others choose a path of solitude, sprouting alone, while some form tight-knit communities, growing in clusters, as if seeking companionship in their brief lives.

The Enigma mushrooms looks different from other strains of psilocybe cubensis. Photo courtesy of Fungi.org.
Morphology, too, can be a box of surprises. The classic image of a mushrooma cap and stemis just the tip of the iceberg. Some appear robust, flaunting their thickened girth, while others take on more delicate, elongated forms. The direction of their growth is a whimsical dance; some reach straight up, extending towards the sky, while others curve, twist, or even daringly grow downwards, as if exploring the mysteries of the earth below.

Yet, among all these variations, there are those truly unexpected outliers: the ones that challenge our very understanding of what a mushroom should look like.
